AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Conflict on GRE: you say F ION - GRE, TUR says A BUL - GRE. One of you gets it, one gets bounced. I am not moving to GRE this fall — I'm taking ADR to ALB and holding SER. If you want GRE, you need to know TUR is going for it too. I will not support either of you into GRE; that's your fight. What I need from you is A TYR moving to BOH or MUN — not toward TRI or VIE. Confirm that move and our arrangement holds. If TYR stays adjacent to my centers, I treat it as a threat and respond accordingly."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "ITA is moving F ION - GRE this fall. You will bounce if you move A BUL - GRE. I am not going to GRE — I'm moving F ADR to ALB and holding SER. If you want to avoid wasting A BUL on a bounce, consider holding BUL or moving toward CON to consolidate. On RUM: Russia has it and I've told them I won't contest it this fall. If you want to pressure RUM from BLA, that's your call — I won't interfere. Our Balkan split stands: BUL yours, SER mine, GRE contested between you and ITA."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Agreed on the division: RUM is yours, I will not move on it this fall. My orders: A SER holds, F ADR moves to ALB. I am not contesting your southern position. In exchange, keep A WAR out of GAL — I have A VIE positioned to bounce you again if needed, and that wastes both our turns. One flag: TUR has A BUL and F BLA — they are your more immediate problem in the south, not me. If BUL moves toward RUM, you'll want to respond. I can hold SER as a buffer if that's useful to you."}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'Confirmed - my orders this fall: F DEN -> SWE, A MUN -> RUH (positioning for HOL next spring), A SIL -> WAR or holds to threaten Russia. I will not contest Belgium - that is yours via F ENG. You take NOR, I take SWE, you take BEL, I take HOL next spring. France is squeezed from both sides. This is the arrangement that wins us both the game in the west. Do not let F NTH wander - I need SWE secured and your fleet in NOR keeps Russia honest in the north.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, I accept your proposal of mutual non-aggression. I am moving to secure Scandinavia this fall - DEN fleet goes to SWE, armies repositioning northward. I have no orders directed at Burgundy or Belgium this fall. Focus on Iberia, I focus on the north - we have no quarrel. England in the Channel is the greater threat to both of us long-term. Let us keep this channel of communication open.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I am moving F DEN to SWE this fall to secure Scandinavia. My army in Silesia will hold or move to PRU - no threat to Warsaw, I give you my word. Austria's bounce of your Galicia move in spring was provocative - they are growing strong in the Balkans with Serbia taken and their fleet in the Adriatic. I would strongly suggest pressing into Galicia this fall while I keep Austria's attention divided. A coordinated Russo-German pressure on Austria benefits us both enormously."}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I've reviewed your proposal carefully. Here are my confirmed fall orders: A BUL moves to GRE, F BLA holds in the Black Sea to maintain pressure on Russia. A CON will support BUL's move to GRE. This means GRE goes to me this fall - I need that center. You should take ALB with F ADR and position for future moves. On RUM: I can support you into RUM from BLA if you have a unit that can reach it, but I don't see how you get there this fall without a unit adjacent. Let's focus on what's achievable: you hold SER, I take GRE, and we both pressure Russia from our respective positions. Confirm your orders so we don't accidentally interfere."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I accept your cold peace proposal for now. My fall orders: A BUL to GRE, F BLA holds. I am not moving into RUM or SEV this fall - Greece is my target, not your territory. In return, keep F RUM out of BUL and A SEV away from ARM. We both grow in different directions this year. However, understand that F BLA remains in the Black Sea permanently - that is non-negotiable. If you respect my sphere, I will respect yours. Next year we can discuss a more formal arrangement regarding RUM and the Balkans.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I see we have a conflict: you are moving F ION toward Greece and I am moving A BUL toward Greece. One of us will be disappointed. I propose you redirect F ION toward Tunis instead - that is a guaranteed center for you with no competition, while Greece is my natural expansion. If we both move on Greece we both risk bouncing and gaining nothing. Take Tunis this fall, I take Greece, and we both end the year with gains. This is the rational outcome for both of us. Please reconsider your move.'}]
