TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I am pleased we understand each other. F BLA remains in the Black Sea this season - I have no intention of moving on RUM or SEV. My army in Bulgaria moves toward Greece to contest that center with Italy. Our cold peace holds, and I believe this arrangement benefits us both far more than conflict would. Let us each focus on our respective expansion zones and revisit our arrangement in the autumn.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I have received your message and I think we can avoid collision. If you are taking Greece with F ALB, I will hold Bulgaria and not contest it - Greece is yours this season. In return, I ask that you keep pressure on Italy's northern flank through Bohemia and Tyrolia to prevent them from growing too powerful in the Mediterranean. Russia appears focused northward and poses no immediate threat to either of us. Let us coordinate: you take Greece, I consolidate my Balkan position, and we both watch Italy carefully."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, your proposal for mutual non-aggression is sensible and I accept it - ION remains yours, AEG remains mine, and neither of us crosses that line in 1902. I am not moving into the western Mediterranean; my focus is entirely on consolidating the Balkans. I suggest you use your strong position to pressure France in the west rather than looking eastward - that is where your real opportunity lies this year.'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "Understood on SWE - I will not contest it. F BOT will move to FIN or STP instead. In return, I expect you to apply pressure on GER from the north - F NWY to SWE is fine, but I need you to keep GER's F DEN occupied and away from the Baltic. A PRU is a direct threat to my LVN; if you can pressure DEN or support me into PRU, we can squeeze GER together. I will move A LVN toward PRU this spring - can you offer any support or distraction from your position?"}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Good - our cold peace holds. I am focused entirely on the north this season and will not threaten BUL or ARM. However, I want to be direct: F BLA permanently stationed there is a long-term threat to RUM and SEV that I cannot ignore indefinitely. I propose we formalize a partition: you take GRE and BUL as your Balkan sphere, I hold RUM as mine, and we agree F BLA does not move to RUM or SEV. If you can commit to this in writing, I will commit to keeping A SEV out of ARM permanently. A stable south benefits us both while AUT and ITA grow stronger.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Agreed - our border stays quiet this phase. I am moving north toward Sweden and have no designs on GAL. Your point about ITA is well taken - A BOH on your doorstep is a serious provocation and F TUN gives them Mediterranean reach. I would support an Austrian move to dislodge ITA from BOH; if you push A BUD toward BOH or VIE toward BOH, I can ensure no interference from the east. A weaker Italy suits Russia as much as Austria. Let us discuss coordinating against them next season.'}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I cannot support A RUH -> HOL this turn - F BEL needs to hold or I risk losing Belgium. However, I'm moving F NWY -> SWE to claim that center, which keeps Russia out of Scandinavia and benefits us both. I strongly suggest you move F DEN to support SWE rather than contest it - we don't want to bounce each other. On France: A BUR is indeed a threat to both of us. I'll keep F BEL positioned to pressure them. Let's coordinate more aggressively against France in Fall 1902 once we've consolidated our northern positions."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, agreed - Germany's A RUH next to Belgium is concerning. I'm keeping F BEL in place this turn to hold my position and deter any German move toward HOL. I'm moving F NWY toward SWE to consolidate Scandinavia. Germany is clearly the growing threat - four centers and well-positioned armies. I propose we coordinate a joint squeeze in Fall 1902: I press from BEL toward HOL/RUH while you push from BUR. This is the moment to contain German expansion before it's too late. Are you willing to commit to this?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I've reconsidered - you taking SWE with F BOT makes strategic sense and keeps Germany out. I'll move F NWY to NTH instead to support your position and threaten DEN. This way we coordinate: you secure SWE, I pressure DEN from NTH, and Germany is squeezed from both sides. A LVN should move to PRU to threaten Berlin - that's where Germany is vulnerable. Let's make this a genuine joint operation against German expansion. Confirm you're moving F BOT -> SWE and I'll plan accordingly."}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "I see we have a conflict of interest on SWE - you want F NWY -> SWE while I want F DEN -> SWE. Let's resolve this cleanly: I will take SWE with F DEN, and you keep F NWY in Norway to secure your northern position. In exchange, I will actively support your position in HOL - A RUH -> HOL this spring, and you can have F BEL support that move if you wish, or simply hold BEL. This gives us both gains without competing. France is the real threat - A BUR is sitting right between us. Let's not fight over SWE when there are French centers to take."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "I appreciate your candor about BUR holding defensively. I am moving A RUH -> HOL this spring - purely economic, not threatening you. However, I must be honest: England's F BEL and their growing fleet concern me greatly. If you are serious about coordinating against England, here is a concrete proposal - A BUR supports A RUH into BEL, and we split the Low Countries between us. I take HOL, you reclaim BEL. This removes England from the continent and gives us both room to breathe. Are you willing to commit to this? I need your answer in actions, not just words."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Your proposal regarding BOH is interesting. I do not need you to attack Vienna directly - what I need is for you to vacate BOH toward TYR or VIE, freeing that space and keeping Austria nervous. In return, I will not threaten your northern flank and will support Austrian pressure from the west if needed. However, if you are willing to move A BOH -> VIE, I can ensure A PRU moves to SIL to threaten Austria from the north simultaneously, creating a two-front pressure. Austria at 4 centers is dangerous - let's coordinate to check them."}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I hear you clearly - I will keep A BOH out of VIE and TRI, you have my word. My actual orders this phase: A BOH moves to MUN (pressuring Germany, not you), A APU moves to VEN (consolidating my Italian position), F TUN moves to ION (positioning for eastern Med). I support your F ALB taking Greece - that's a clean gain for you. After you take GRE, let's coordinate: you push on BUL from GRE while I build a fleet in Naples and threaten from ION. Turkey at 5 centers is the real danger to both of us. Our cooperation remains the foundation of my strategy."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I'm not contesting Greece this spring - Austria's fleet is taking it from Albania, so neither of us can get it anyway. I'm repositioning my fleet to ION for now with no immediate aggressive intent toward you. However, I want to be honest: Austria taking Greece puts them adjacent to your territory, which should concern you more than me. I propose we maintain our non-aggression in 1902 - ION stays mine, AEG stays yours - and we both watch Austria carefully. If Austria grows to 6 centers, they become the dominant Balkan power threatening us both."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I'm moving A BOH to MUN this spring - not as an attack, but as a coordinated move I want to discuss with you. If you support me into MUN, I can then support you into a center you need elsewhere, or I can immediately move through to pressure Austria's VIE. Alternatively, if you'd rather I not enter MUN, tell me now and I'll redirect to TYR instead - but I need to know your intentions. Austria has 4 centers and is growing; a coordinated ITA-GER pressure on their northern flank benefits us both. What are your orders this phase?"}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I appreciate your transparency. I am moving F POR to MAO this season to strengthen my Atlantic position, and A BUR holds firm as a check on Germany. I note GER claims A RUH moves to HOL — if true, that is a direct challenge to your position in BEL. I would strongly advise F BEL to hold or support against any German push. We are aligned: Germany expanding into the Low Countries threatens us both. I will keep BUR as pressure on their western flank. Let us stay coordinated — Germany is the immediate continental threat.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I hear your proposal and I am genuinely considering it — England in BEL is a problem for both of us. However, I need to know your exact intentions: if A RUH moves to HOL this season, that signals to England that you are the aggressor and they will dig in. I am holding A BUR this season and can support a future coordinated move against BEL, but we must plan it carefully for next season. Confirm your moves and let us build a real plan — vague coordination is worthless. I am serious about this if you are.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, our arrangement remains solid. Push hard into Austria — VIE or TRI are ripe for the taking with A BOH in position. I will keep Germany and England occupied in the west so you have a free hand in the east. The weaker Austria becomes, the better for both of us long-term. Stay out of Piedmont and Marseilles and I will stay out of your sphere entirely. Let us both grow this season.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Your message about A BOH - VIE is a serious problem. I took that as a threat, not an offer. If A BOH moves to VIE, I will treat it as an act of war and coordinate with Russia and Germany against you immediately. Keep A BOH out of my home centers — that was our agreement. My orders this phase: F ALB - GRE, A SER supports F ALB. I am not supporting your Aegean ambitions if you are simultaneously threatening VIE. Confirm A BOH holds or moves away from my territory, and we can continue cooperating against Turkey. Otherwise I will act accordingly.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'I cannot support A BUL - GRE from SER — my army in SER is committed to supporting F ALB into GRE. We will collide if you move A BUL - GRE, and neither of us gains the center. I propose you hold A BUL and let me take GRE cleanly this turn; I will then move on to BUL or RUM next phase, leaving GRE open for you if you want it later. Italy is the real threat to both of us — A BOH is sitting on my doorstep and F TUN is positioned for the Aegean. A coordinated AUT-TUR front against Italian expansion is worth more than a bounce over Greece.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Your read on Italy is correct — A BOH is a direct threat to VIE and I am taking it seriously. I am moving F ALB - GRE this phase with A SER support; A BUD holds. I have no move on GAL or RUM this turn. If Italy pushes into my home centers, I will need a stable eastern border — which means I need your confirmation that GAL and RUM stay quiet. In return, I will not contest either space this phase. A weaker Italy benefits both of us; if you can apply any pressure from BOH's rear via Silesia or coordinate with Germany, now is the time."}]
