TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, agreed - Italy's F ION is the immediate threat to both of us. My plan this fall: A BUL holds to secure our Balkan buffer, F RUM holds in place, A CON moves to SMY to reposition. I am not moving against you or Russia this season - pure consolidation. Next spring I want to coordinate a joint squeeze on Italy: you press from the north with A SER and F GRE threatens AEG, while I position F RUM to eventually enter the Adriatic sphere. Italy at 4 centers with BOH and ION is dangerous - let's agree now that we both target ITA expansion next year. Hold your southern line stable this fall and we plan the joint strike for S1903."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, I appreciate the directness, but I do not hold GRE - Austria took it this season with F ALB moving to GRE. Check the board: F GRE belongs to Austria, not me. My units are A BUL, F RUM, A CON. I hold 5 centers: ANK, CON, SMY, BUL, RUM. GRE is Austria's problem, not mine. The ION/AEG line remains intact on my end - I have no fleet in AEG and no designs on your Mediterranean position. Focus your energy on Austria if GRE is your target. I will stay out of it."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, the cold peace holds - F RUM stays where it is and I have no designs on SEV. A ARM moving westward is noted; I trust it is not heading toward ANK. My moves this fall are purely consolidating: holding BUL and RUM, repositioning A CON to SMY. I propose we formalize this: F RUM stays out of SEV, A ARM stays out of ANK and ARM stays away from Turkish home centers, and we both grow elsewhere. You have Sweden to contest and Germany pressing you - focus there. I will focus on the Balkans. A stable southern front is in both our interests.'}]
