[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, your proposal to move A BUL toward GRE is exactly what I do not want — that threatens my center, not Italy's. Here is what I am actually doing this spring: F GRE moves to AEG, A SER holds, A BUD holds. I am not contesting BUL or RUM. If you want to coordinate against Italy, the correct move is for you to hold BUL firm while I use F GRE to pressure F ION from AEG. That pins Italy's fleet without either of us colliding. I need BUL to stay put this turn — if A BUL moves toward GRE we will bounce and both waste the phase. Confirm you will hold BUL and I will execute the AEG move as stated."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, here is my concrete offer: I will support A GAL into BOH this spring — order A BUD S A GAL - BOH. That dislodges Italy's army from BOH and removes the threat to both of us. In return I need A GAL to move to BOH and not to RUM or VIE. If you execute A GAL - BOH and I support it, Italy loses their northern foothold. My other units: F GRE to AEG, A SER holds. I am not touching GAL or RUM. This is a clean coordinated move — confirm you will order A GAL - BOH and I will issue the support."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, your anti-Turkey framing is noted but your F ION is still adjacent to GRE and A BOH is still adjacent to my home centers — words are cheap. Here is what changes my calculus: move A BOH to MUN or TYR away from my territory, and move F ION to AEG or TYR SEA away from GRE. If you do both, I will not support Russia into BOH and I will coordinate F GRE into AEG alongside your fleet against Turkey. If A BOH stays where it is, I am supporting Russia to dislodge it this turn. Your choice is simple: retreat north and we have a deal, or hold and lose the army.'}]
