[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "The F1903M result is clear: ITA holds VIE and TRI, I hold BUD and SER. The coordinated push failed because ITA's A BOH - VIE succeeded before your support could land. We need to reassess. My position: A BUD and A SER. Your position: A BOH, A SEV, F BOT. The path back for me runs through VIE — I need A BUD - VIE with your A BOH supporting. That dislodges ITA from VIE and puts me back in my home center. What can you commit to this spring? I can support your A BOH in place or into GAL if you need it, but the VIE push is my absolute priority. Tell me your intended orders and I will coordinate mine around them."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "ITA now holds VIE and TRI — six centers, three units, and sitting on my heartland. This is the threat I warned you about. I am coordinating with RUS to retake VIE this spring. I need your assurance that A BUL holds and F BLA does not move toward RUM — I cannot fight ITA if I am watching my southern flank. In exchange, I will not contest BUL, RUM, or GRE this phase. You benefit from ITA being pushed back before they build a fleet and threaten the Aegean. Confirm your defensive posture and we both gain from ITA's setback."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "ITA is at six centers with VIE and TRI. You hold MUN — A TYR is one move from your doorstep if ITA builds and pushes west. The threat is mutual. I am pushing A BUD toward VIE this spring with RUS support from BOH. I need you to move A MUN toward TYR or A WAR toward BOH to pin ITA's units and prevent them from reinforcing VIE. If VIE falls back to me, ITA drops to five and loses momentum. What can you commit?"}]
